<item>
  <title>Selection and Insertion Sorts</title>
  <dc:creator>Vikram Dixit</dc:creator>
  <link>https://VikkiD.github.io/TechEcon/posts/selection-insertion-sorts/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 




<p>Sorting is one of the most basic approaches to solving problems in human thought. Be it prioritizing which tasks to tackle first or who to pay first; ranking in competitions, exams, and any other comparative decisions — we are sorting. It is a fundamental problem in computer science too: organizing records by date, tabulating results into a sequence of some kind. In this post we look at two of the simplest sort algorithms — selection sort and insertion sort. They are instructive, and although less efficient than other algorithms on large, randomly ordered data, they remain widely used at small sizes and on streaming data. The goal here is to introduce both and, in a companion post, put one to work on a real puzzle.</p>
<section id="selection-sort" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="selection-sort">Selection Sort</h2>
<p>The idea: repeatedly <em>select</em> the smallest remaining value and place it in the next position — smallest into slot 0, next-smallest into slot 1, and so on until every element is placed.</p>
<div class="tabset-margin-container"></div><div class="panel-tabset">
<ul class="nav nav-tabs"><li class="nav-item"><a class="nav-link active" id="tabset-1-1-tab" data-bs-toggle="tab" data-bs-target="#tabset-1-1" aria-controls="tabset-1-1" aria-selected="true" href="">Pseudocode</a></li><li class="nav-item"><a class="nav-link" id="tabset-1-2-tab" data-bs-toggle="tab" data-bs-target="#tabset-1-2" aria-controls="tabset-1-2" aria-selected="false" href="">Python</a></li></ul>
<div class="tab-content">
<div id="tabset-1-1" class="tab-pane active" aria-labelledby="tabset-1-1-tab">
<pre><code>SELECTION-SORT(a):
    n ← length(a)
    for i ← 0 to n-1:
        min ← i
        for j ← i+1 to n-1:
            if a[j] &lt; a[min]:
                min ← j
        swap a[i] and a[min]      # at most n-1 swaps total
    return a</code></pre>
