<section id="where-these-still-earn-their-keep" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="where-these-still-earn-their-keep">Where these still earn their keep</h2>
<!-- Expand these in your own voice --- each is a real, checkable claim: -->
<ul>
<li><strong>Insertion sort is <em>online</em>.</strong> It can absorb elements one at a time as they arrive, keeping the array sorted after each insertion — so it fits streaming input, where a divide-and-conquer sort would have to wait for the whole batch.</li>
<li><strong>Insertion sort is <em>adaptive</em>.</strong> On nearly-sorted input the inner loop hits the <code>break</code> almost immediately, so it approaches O(n). This is why real-world hybrid sorts (like the Timsort behind Python’s own <code>sorted</code>) fall back to insertion sort on short runs, where its low overhead beats an asymptotically faster algorithm.</li>
<li><strong>Selection sort minimizes writes.</strong> Its n − 1 swaps make it attractive when writing is costly or wearing — the seed of the companion post’s puzzle.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Next:</em> an applied post that takes the “fewest exchanges” idea and runs with it — sorting a deck of cards laid face down, where every exchange is the costly move.</p>


